          <p class='first-para'>
            I, too, congratulate the hon. Member for Cotswold (Mr. Clifton-Brown) on introducing the debate. I saw the title of his intended debate last week and thought that it would provide the opportunity to bring together several different issues, but when I listened to the hon. Gentleman this morning, he suggested a closer connection between the issues than actually exists.</p><p>
            Hon. Members may know that, for several years, I have been involved with the Bristol heart action group, which brings together the relatives of those whose babies
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_12wh' title='Col. 12WH &mdash; HC Deb 14 December 1999 vol 341 c12WH' name='column_12wh' href='#column_12wh' rel='bookmark'>12WH</a>
            died in the tragedy at Bristol royal infirmary. In that connection, I have recently taken an interest in events at Alder Hey hospital, and there is now a connection between the two groups of parents.</p><p>
            The hon. Member for Cotswold said that no one was accusing doctors of deliberately removing organs without the consent of relatives&#x2014;
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution'>
        <a name='S6CV0341P0_19991214_WH_27'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-geoffrey-clifton-brown' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
